Observation Details: These photographs made me recall a comment by an awestruck boy of ten or eleven who was along on a bird walk I led in my Massachusetts town about forty years ago.  He was staring at a bird through his binoculars and exclaimed, "it is _so_ beautiful."  I looked, and seeing "only" a starling I identified it—dismissively—to another adult who was present.  The photos show that the boy (David, who in later years taught middle school history to my daughter) was right and I was wrong.

Observation Details: Thoroughly fascinating to watch. At the main rock platform (just back a bit from the cafe - and the jetty under construction) and also on Bare Island, these birds were foraging among sea weeds and other marine life, effectively occupying the niche you'd expect of shorebirds like Red-necked Stints. Waves would sometimes crash over them and they'd fly a few metres off but invariably return to continue feeding. The feeding action was fascinating - they would basically open their bills as wide as possible and jab straight into the marine flora/fauna. The photo with two birds back to back captures this well. It was as if in that position they were testing if they could loosen or move anything, before pulling their head back (and bills back out of the seaweeds) and sometimes they'd have a small morsel they'd toss a few times as they gulped it back. Others walked along seemingly bare rock and pecked at it - possibly picking up the most minute of bugs or perhaps even loose algae. The birds on Bare Island in particular were surprisingly confiding.

At the main rock platform (just back a bit from the cafe - and the jetty under construction) and also on Bare Island, these birds were foraging among sea weeds and other marine life, effectively occupying the niche you'd expect of shorebirds like Red-necked Stints. Waves would sometimes crash over them and they'd fly a few metres off but invariably return to continue feeding. The feeding action was fascinating - they would basically open their bills as wide as possible and jab straight into the marine flora/fauna. The photo with two birds back to back captures this well. It was as if in that position they were testing if they could loosen or move anything, before pulling their head back (and bills back out of the seaweeds) and sometimes they'd have a small morsel they'd toss a few times as they gulped it back. Others walked along seemingly bare rock and pecked at it - possibly picking up the most minute of bugs or perhaps even loose algae. The birds on Bare Island in particular were surprisingly confiding.

Some symbiosis going on here between only this black steer #8 (among ten other clearly visible fly-covered faces) and the starling. It was eating the flies off its face ... including pecking near the eye. And ... even the starling has flies.

Observation Details: Along the west side of Sutton Rd there is a EUST nest in a cavity in a large tree. Today I became aware of a commotion of EUST and as I got close to the tree I noted a young EUST at the entrance of the nest. As I looked more closed I saw a chipmunk looking out at me with a mouthful of starling. As the starling struggled the two fell out of the nest to the ground at the base of the tree. As I left the young starling seemed to be in great peril, the chipmunk was not a skilled predator and the starling was experiencing a slow death.

Historical record. I wasn't a birder yet but my interest was developing. I was walking in DC with my Mom and I saw this bird walking quickly across the courtyard. I pointed it out to my mother. I had never seen a Starling before, strangely enough, and I thought it was gorgeous with the iridescent sparkles on its wings. I chased it until I got this very poor shot. I never did a report for the day but I always remember this was the first time I saw a Starling. I didn't even know what it was called when I followed it.

Observation Details: These photographs made me recall a comment by an awestruck boy of ten or eleven who was along on a bird walk I led in my Massachusetts town about forty years ago.  He was staring at a bird through his binoculars and exclaimed, "it is _so_ beautiful."  I looked, and seeing "only" a starling I identified it—dismissively—to another adult who was present.  The photos show that the boy (David, who in later years taught middle school history to my daughter) was right and I was wrong.

Observation Details: Photographed and watched two Starlings fighting for 5+ minutes. The pair locked legs and plummeted to the ground together. One remained on top for the duration of the fight - periodically pecking and wing flapping down on the other. The one on the bottom made repeated alarm notes. They were undisturbed by the presence of people and tightly locked together. Eventually both flew off in the same direction. Wild -- I've never seen anything like it.
